	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>4th to 5th generation biggest leap?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Even though I always thought 3d polygons looked ugly until 7th generation systems, I always thought jumping from 2d to 3d was the biggest leap in video game graphics.  From researching technical specs I can also make a point that it was also the biggest leap in processor efficiency.<br /><br />Reasons:<br />- Memory was finally large enough for double buffering.<br />- Memory was finally fast enough for GPUs to fetch a single pixel at a time, allowing individual pixel manipulation, as opposed to fetching groups of several pixels at a time.<br />- CDs got rid of some of the memory constraints of cartridges.<br />- Any design flaws of 4th gen systems such as the Genesis's lack of available colors, or SNES's unflexible sprite management.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


