	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><ol style="list-style-type: decimal"><li>Discrete logic games (Odyssey, Pong, etc.) </li><li>Early 8-bit microprocessor consoles (Fairchild Channel F, VideoBrain Family Computer, Atari 2600, Videopac/Odyssey 2, Atari 5200, Intellivision) </li><li>Late 8-bit: Nintendo Family Computer/NES, Atari 7800, Sega Mark III/SMS </li><li>16-bit: Genesis, Super NES, Neo Geo </li><li>Early 32-bit: PlayStation, Nintendo 64 </li><li>Late 32-bit: Dreamcast, PlayStation 2, GameCube, Xbox </li><li>Early downloadable: Xbox 360, PlayStation 3 </li><li>Late downloadable: Xbox One, PlayStation 4 </li></ol><br />Yes, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/VideoBrain_Family_Computer" class="postlink">VideoBrain had its own Famicom</a>, which I guess is part of why Nintendo changed the name outside Japan.<br /><br />Having been ninja'd, I feel the need to add this: Some consoles are &quot;intergenerational&quot; in their capability, offering some but not all features of the next generation. These include SG-1000 and ColecoVision/Adam (2 going on 3), PC Engine/TurboGrafx-16 (3 going on 4), Jaguar and 3DO and 32X (4 going on 5), Wii (6 going on 7), Wii U and OUYA (7 going on 8).<br /><br />The original Odyssey was discrete logic but had jumper paks to reconfigure the circuits for each game.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


