		<td><b>Re: 4th to 5th generation biggest leap?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />True, but the 3D leap was still important because it allowed for a behind-the-character viewpoint. Behind-the-character allows for far longer distances than a side or overhead view. Otherwise, when a character is moving rapidly across the landscape, the player can't react in time to obstacles or items that just scrolled into view. This let games get away from a &quot;world map&quot;, &quot;town map&quot;, and &quot;indoor map&quot; at three separate scales in favor of one seamless map, leading to the whole sandbox genre.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


