		<td><b>Re: 4th to 5th generation biggest leap?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />4th to 5th (2D to 3D) was the biggest leap.<br /><br />It was just a different world going from tile-map style side-scrolling graphics to more or less a free-roaming kind of game style.<br /><br />But I do remember it was more smooth of a transition given what the arcade machines were doing in the late 80's to early 90's. 5th generation was when the processing power necessary to match them became affordable to the home market. But it was also the first generation where it became infeasible for a one-person operation to produce, package, and sell a game. So for a time it was an explosion of fresh new game studios and new ideas.<br /><br />On the technical side, it became necessary to develop the 3D cad tools that non-technical artists could use. Everything that wasn't &quot;3D&quot; looking was deemed antiquated (for a time). Though there are still some hints of this where certain fighting games tout the &quot;hand-drawn&quot; characters as a sort of throwback selling point. Motion capture (mo-cap) was also a really big deal in this 3D era, as it turns out that natural-looking motion is incredibly difficult to fake.<br /> <br /><br />As for anomalies, or games ahead of their time:<br />It seems one can always find a game of a previous generation that used the ideas or technologies prevalent in the subsequent generation.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


