		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Advanced graphical capabilities while still using an 8-bit CPU?</div><br />I figured the 8bit attribute would just be an argument for semantics, and not what was capable or delivered (end result). The processing capability of the cpu was about on pair with the Genesis, and faster than the snes - regardless of the size of the ALU and registers.<br /><br /> Putting a 16bit processor in the machine wouldn't have changed anything (a 68k at the same speed, actually would have made it slower on interrupt handling code, especially full screen hsync effect, and slower overall), other than the labels of 'bits'. If anything, I would say the exclusion of a separate sound processor - since the snes and genesis had those. Though that's rather minor, and the success of, and inclusion of, the CD unit with CD audio makes that sort of a null point. <br /><br /><br /> What makes a system inter-generational, rather than the basis for that generation?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I don't know... It did have pretty advanced graphics for the time (4bpp tiles), but things like the amount of VRAM, the small color palette and the low limit of sprites per scanline prevented the graphics from looking significantly superior to the other consoles.</div><br />Golden Axe looks pretty impressive, especially compared to the NES. There were a few other titles that used similar tricks (vram characters along with sprites) that looked impressive. Asterix and Streets of Rage look pretty impressive too. Phantasy Star could pass as an early 16bit RPG.

		

